    public int orangesRotting(int[][] grid) { 
        // 1. Edge Case: If the grid doesn't exist, no time is needed 
        if(grid == null || grid.length == 0) return 0; 
        int rows = grid.length;
         int cols = grid[0].length; 
         // Queue stores coordinates [row, col] of oranges that are currently rotten 
        Queue<int[]> queue = new LinkedList<>();
         int count_fresh = 0; 
         // 2. Initial Scan:  
       // Find all initially rotten oranges to start the BFS and count fresh ones 
        for(int i = 0 ; i < rows ; i++) {  
           for(int j = 0 ; j < cols ; j++) { 
                if(grid[i][j] == 2) {  
                   queue.offer(new int[]{i , j}); 
                  // Add to start of "infection"  
               } 
               else if(grid[i][j] == 1) {  
                   count_fresh++;
                // We need to track these to see if they all rot
                 }   
          }   
      }  
        // If there are no fresh oranges to begin with, 0 minutes have passed  
       if(count_fresh == 0) return 0;  
        int count = 0; 
        // Tracks minutes passed 
        // 4-Directional movement: Down, Up, Right, Left   
      int[][] dirs = {{1,0},{-1,0},{0,1},{0,-1}};   
       // 3. BFS Process:  
       While(!queue.isEmpty()) {  
           ++count; // Increment time as we move to the next "layer" of oranges  
           int size = queue.size(); // Number of oranges rotting others at THIS minute   
           for(int i = 0 ; i < size ; i++) {  
               int[] point = queue.poll();   
                for(int dir[] : dirs) {   
                  int x = point[0] + dir[0];  
                   int y = point[1] + dir[1]; 
                     // Skip if: Out of bounds, cell is empty (0), or orange is already rotten (2) 
                    if(x < 0 || y < 0 || x >= rows || y >= cols || grid[x][y] == 0 || grid[x][y] == 2) {   
                      continue;                     }   
                       // "Infect" the fresh orange   
                  grid[x][y] = 2;   
                  // Add new rotten orange to queue to infect neighbors in the NEXT minute    
                 queue.offer(new int[]{x , y});   
                  // One less fresh orange remains in the grid   
                  count_fresh--;   
              }   
          } 
        }  
        // 4. Final Result:   
     // If count_fresh is 0, all oranges rotted.  
        // We return 'count - 1' because the last level of BFS adds a minute even if no  
        // new oranges were actually infected in the final loop.  
       // If count_fresh > 0, it means some oranges are unreachable; return -1. 
        return count_fresh == 0 ? count - 1 : -1;  
   } 

 Time Complexity:  
Scanning the Grid:
 You first traverse every cell once to find initially rotten oranges and count fresh ones, which takes   time. 
BFS Traversal:
 In the worst-case scenario, every cell contains a fresh orange that eventually rots. 
Since each cell is added to the queue at most once and processed once, the BFS also takes   time. 
Total:  O(MxN)+O((MxN)=O(MxN) where   is the number of rows and   is the number of columns.  
Space Complexity: 
 Queue Storage: 
In the worst case, the queue may need to store all the cells in the grid simultaneously 
(e.g., if all oranges are rotten at the start or if a large "wave" of oranges rots at once). 
Total:  O(MXN) to account for the auxiliary space used by the queue. 
